Perhaps a fisheye lens is a bit too much for a nesting box.
One never learns.
I should have known better, since I had built one with a "normal" lens before.
I will write more about it over the weekend, as soon as I have installed the second one.
Let's just say that the birds will have a better internet connection than I did in 2015.
At least that's the plan.
The box that already has a nest is consuming a lot of WiFi data.
It will be a bit harder for the other one to go online.
Okay, I hung up the new nesting box today. This is how it looks like at its new place in the garden.
But let's go back a bit. No one asks: "What exactly is inside it?"
Up top is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a camera featuring a fisheye lens and an IR LED, which I took from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the strange shape of this plastic box is the hinged side wall of the nesting box. I bought it like that and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there is no power in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here's a picture of the panel.
In the gray box hanging next to the nesting box is the battery.
When it's fully charged, I have a runtime of about 4 hours.
I'd call that a feature. That way, the birds also get some privacy.
At first, I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be enough for this setup. The old access points that I replaced last fall wouldn't have been sufficient.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
That's almost a shame, because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and set it up pointing down into the garden.
Perhaps I will do that when/fall I set up more nesting boxes with cameras. I will probably need that in areas further away from the house.
Now the camera is offline and I don't know why. It only shut down an hour after sunset.
Maybe the battery didn't charge for three hours before sunset because there wasn't enough light.
Or less than half a day was too little to fully charge the battery.
I'll probably have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have any telemetry for the battery. I might have to change that in the future.
Generally, a few more sensors would be a good thing, I think.
And maybe a battery that can, at least theoretically, keep the thing running overnight.
Oh yes, and another lens.
Fisheye is quite overdone.
But I'm already looking for parts at Digikey so I can build my own board exactly for that.
Or maybe not. We'll see.
And it's still offline.
Great.
According to the actual solar panels on the house, we only get about 90 minutes of direct sunlight.
Let's wait another or two hours to see what happens – or doesn't happen.
Still offline.
It's never easy, after all.
It turned out that in the USB-C breakout board I used to connect the charger, 5 V and GND were swapped on the silk screen.
I swapped the cables and now the charging indicator is lit.
The ESP didn't come online immediately. Let's wait for a few minutes.
An hour has passed and it's still offline.
It looks like it's restarting and triggering a Tasmota reset function.
I think the panel just doesn't work. I've ordered a larger one now and hope that one will work then.
Look, what I found in my workshop.
A 24-V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is already so low (and partly blocked by a tree) that the value practically drops to zero as soon as I turn the device on.
I will likely have to wait until tomorrow to see if it is sufficient for this setup or if I need the better panel that I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021, and it is supposed to deliver 12 V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
So either something is wrong with the panel or my multimeter, or the data has been changed.
Good news!
They have changed the data, and the one I have is wrong.
The old listing title and also the new one call it a 12 V 10 W panel.
That's why I never delete old emails.
Oh look! The thing went online again about an hour ago, for about half a minute.
Maybe the panel just charged the battery long enough for 38 seconds of operation. It took it a bit more than two hours to do so.
Guess what: It's cloudy today. I'm not sure if the (probably broken) solar panel will even manage to generate enough power.
Let's wait and see.
Update: I've installed the new panel and now it seems to be working.
It could still fail as soon as the sun sets, but let's give it a chance.
Fun fact: I use the Ping integration in Home Assistant to see if it's online or not.
The average connection time is 102 ms. Not particularly good, but not crazy bad either.
